butler
stood
before
them,
making
final
adjustments
on
the
white
tie
and
tuxedo
he
had
apparently
just
donned.
He
looked
to
be
about
fifty,
with
refined
features
and
an
austere
expression
that
left
little
doubt
he
was
unamused
by
their
presence
here.
"Sir
Leigh
will
be
down
presently,"
he
declared,
his
accent
thick
French.
"He
is
dressing.
He
prefers
not
to
greet
visitors
while
wearing
only
a
nightshirt.
May
I
take
your
coat?"
He
scowled
at
the
bunched
up
tweed
in
Langdon'
s
arms.
"Thank
you,
I'm
fine."
"Of
course
you
are.
Right
this
way,
please."
The
butler
guided
them
through
a
lush
marble
foyer
into
an
exquisitely
adorned
drawing
room,
softly
lit
by
tassel
